    "body": "@TomAugspurger I have noticed that MultiIndex row labels are top-aligned in the default display, but are middle-aligned when used with `DataFrame.style.format()`.   For example : \r\n\r\n<img width=\"742\" alt=\"image\" src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1406529/53281165-4f732b00-36e1-11e9-9e18-834661beb557.png\">\r\n\r\ncompared with \r\n\r\n<img width=\"387\" alt=\"image\" src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1406529/53281174-73367100-36e1-11e9-954d-9dfc20716130.png\">\r\n\r\nI find the top aligned row labels much easier to read (although I can see the appeal of the middle-aligned labels).  Is there a way to get top-aligned labels when using `style.format` ? "
